comment_message_cleaned: I'm curious to know Stumph, where did you study soil science? »"the amount of each determines the general polarity of the soil"« I will admit that I was slightly wrong when I said earlier that soil has a negative charge. What I meant, and should have stated it better, is that the clay particles in the soil have a negative charge. The soil, as whole, (which would include both the clay particles in the soil and the minerals bound by the clay) actually has no electric charge. Whether I choose to have my own vegetable garden, some chickens and a milk cow to feed myself, or simply buy my food at a store is irrelevant to the fact that I am a farmer who makes my living growing crops.

"the solution to overgrazing is to manage the animals properly, overseeing their feeding patterns." What precisely are you overseeing and managing that reduces the amount of plants livestock eat? The reality is acres of land yields pounds of plant based food which in turn will yield only pounds of meat. . "Animals disturb the soil just enough to stimulate new growth and then they fertilize it with their own waste. No machine can do that." This may be true, but there is simply too much animal waste being produced. Large quantities of it get dumped in the ocean causing ocean dead zones. Also, we don't need to be eating the animals in order for them to graze and fertilize land. . "Even if cattle put out ten times the methane they did, even if every human didn’t eat meat, we’d still have to deal with desertification on a global scale, according to Allan." What? Like... what? This just makes no sense. If we stopped raising animals for food there would be fewer animals producing methane thus less methane in the atmosphere. . "Reducing the number of animals on land by culling does not work, either." Well duh! We need to reduce the number of animals on the planet by not multiplying them not by killing the ones that already exist. Suffice to say your argument is absolutely ridiculous and founded on incorrect science and mistruths.

comment_message_cleaned: If we are looking at cattle and habitat destruction vs cars, then, yes, cattle and other livestock may contribute more greenhouse gasses. But the error in the calculation that livestock are worse is that for vehicles, in fairness, habitat destruction and support industry must also be factored. For example, few people stop to think of the millions of acres chewed up to make roads, highways and parking areas. There are whole fields of engineering and city planning devoted to just this, and the sum of destroyed land is vast. The automotive manufacturing and maintenance industries which must mine and manufacture adds to the devastation. The fossil fuel industry, as well as other complex chemical industries for paints, lubricants, etc., adds also to the devastation. Either way it's very bad, though livestock have one saving grace. When raised under more natural conditions, such as the natural grazing conditions of pre-industrial farming, they go a long way toward establishing balance in meadow environments. However, given the massive human overpopulation of the planet, and the ensuing need to cultivate and farm nearly every available scrap of ground in a race against erosion, even that potential benefit is negated.

comment_message_cleaned: ''This spring I was privileged to visit the Africa Centre for Holistic Management (ACHM) in Zimbabwe, and spend several days with Allan Savory, the pioneer and guru of holistic management and managed grazing. Savory is a research biologist who has faced his share of controversy over the years. And you start to get an idea of why this is so, when you hear him utter the phrase: “Only livestock can save us.” A more radical statement could hardly be uttered in this day and age. The media—from newscasts to environmental activists—all seem to agree on this one point: animals are the cause of global warming and we need fewer animals on the planet, not more, if we are to reverse desertification and restore the earth’s grasslands. Allan unabashedly holds and eresses his radically different opinion, at every turn. I was able to talk with him and see the results of his ideas applied practically at the ACHM last May. At this learning hub in Victoria Falls, the Savory Institute staff and volunteers manage the land in a way that is sustainable and regenerative. And livestock are the tool that is turning everything around.'

comment_message_cleaned: The billion cows that are alive and in human possession (and therefore part of the human ecological footprint) outweigh their billion owners :1 and outconsume them :1. Why? Because they are constantly growing, and are slaughtered in adolescence. Historically, ranching has been, and continues to be responsible for systematic destruction of arable land. Attributing the word "sustainable" to any form of raising ruminants requires an extremely myopic understanding of global depletion and non-scientific commentary like, "best nutrition for their brain development" (what nutrient is that?). What makes modern man intelligent is his cerebral cortex, which is used for understanding. Unfortunately, our collective brains are overruled by our taste buds. What I'd like to talk about is modern man's wisdom which, in lacking quantity, is ruining the planet. What report card grade would you give mankind?
